		<summary type="html">&lt;div id=&quot;mp-tfa-img&quot; style=&quot;float: left; margin: 0.5em 0.9em 0.4em 0em;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;thumbinner mp-thumb&quot; style=&quot;background: transparent; border: none; padding: 0; max-width: 100px;&quot;&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/File:Celestial_map_Hyi.svg&quot; title=&quot;Map of Hydrus&quot;&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;Map of Hydrus&quot; src=&quot;//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/bb/Celestial_map_Hyi.png/100px-Celestial_map_Hyi.png&quot; width=&quot;100&quot; height=&quot;117&quot; srcset=&quot;//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/bb/Celestial_map_Hyi.png/150px-Celestial_map_Hyi.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/b/bb/Celestial_map_Hyi.png 2x&quot; data-file-width=&quot;200&quot; data-file-height=&quot;234&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Hydrus&quot; title=&quot;Hydrus&quot;&gt;Hydrus&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/b&gt; is a small &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Constellation&quot; title=&quot;Constellation&quot;&gt;constellation&lt;/a&gt; in the deep southern sky. Its first appearance was on a celestial globe published in 1598 in Amsterdam by the astronomer &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Petrus_Plancius&quot; title=&quot;Petrus Plancius&quot;&gt;Petrus Plancius&lt;/a&gt; and the cartographer &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Jodocus_Hondius&quot; title=&quot;Jodocus Hondius&quot;&gt;Jodocus Hondius&lt;/a&gt;. The first &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Celestial_cartography&quot; title=&quot;Celestial cartography&quot;&gt;celestial atlas&lt;/a&gt; to depict it was &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Johann_Bayer&quot; title=&quot;Johann Bayer&quot;&gt;Johann Bayer&lt;/a&gt;'s &lt;i&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Uranometria&quot; title=&quot;Uranometria&quot;&gt;Uranometria&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/i&gt;, in 1603. The French explorer and astronomer &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Nicolas-Louis_de_Lacaille&quot; title=&quot;Nicolas-Louis de Lacaille&quot;&gt;Nicolas Louis de Lacaille&lt;/a&gt;  charted the brighter stars and gave their &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Bayer_designation&quot; title=&quot;Bayer designation&quot;&gt;Bayer designations&lt;/a&gt; in 1756. Its name means &quot;male water snake&quot;, as opposed to &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Hydra_(constellation)&quot; title=&quot;Hydra (constellation)&quot;&gt;Hydra&lt;/a&gt;, a much larger constellation that represents a female water snake. Hydrus remains below the horizon for most Northern Hemisphere observers. The brightest star is the 2.8-&lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Apparent_magnitude&quot; title=&quot;Apparent magnitude&quot;&gt;magnitude&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Beta_Hydri&quot; title=&quot;Beta Hydri&quot;&gt;Beta Hydri&lt;/a&gt;, also the brightest star within &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Declination&quot; title=&quot;Declination&quot;&gt;15°&lt;/a&gt; of the &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Pole_star#Southern_pole_star_.28South_Star.29&quot; title=&quot;Pole star&quot;&gt;south celestial pole&lt;/a&gt;. Pulsating between magnitude 3.26 and 3.33, &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Gamma_Hydri&quot; title=&quot;Gamma Hydri&quot;&gt;Gamma Hydri&lt;/a&gt; is a variable &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Red_giant&quot; title=&quot;Red giant&quot;&gt;red giant&lt;/a&gt; some 60 times the diameter of our &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Sun&quot; title=&quot;Sun&quot;&gt;Sun&lt;/a&gt;. Near it is &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/VW_Hydri&quot; title=&quot;VW Hydri&quot;&gt;VW Hydri&lt;/a&gt;, one of the brightest &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Dwarf_nova&quot; title=&quot;Dwarf nova&quot;&gt;dwarf novae&lt;/a&gt; in the heavens. Four star systems have been found to have &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Exoplanet&quot; title=&quot;Exoplanet&quot;&gt;exoplanets&lt;/a&gt; to date, including &lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/HD_10180&quot; title=&quot;HD 10180&quot;&gt;HD 10180&lt;/a&gt;, which might bear up to nine planetary companions. (&lt;a href=&quot;/wiki/Hydrus&quot; title=&quot;Hydrus&quot;&gt;&lt;b&gt;Full&amp;#160;article...&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/a&gt;)
&lt;/p&gt;
